I'm not sure about anything else on the menu, but Dannie's large order Orange Chicken (with free small carton of white rice) and pot stickers are where the money is at.  I picked up one of their paper menus-so I can order over the phone and pick up at the store-but the Pot Stickers aren't on the menu. Not sure what they're listed as but they'll know what you're asking for. The sauce they serve with them is excellent. If you spend more than $20, they even give you two free egg rolls.  Pro tip: put two cups of white rice to boil, steam some broccoli and snap peas and in 15 minutes, your order will be ready and you've got a feast.

Save yourself the disappointment. Back in the late 80s it was another company and was a huge staple in dc.  But this place serves “old” fries and re-cooks them. They forgot something I asked for three times when I placed the order.  This  newer generation of Chinese restaurateurs cook Chinese food with no flavor, sub-par service and a whole lot of excuses!  Smh. I’m from a family of chefs- my mother and sister stopped eating from Chinese restaurants a long time ago! They don’t respect those of us that keeps them in business. My best friend is married to an Asian and his parents are in the culinary industry and says to their daughter-in-law do NOT eat at Asian places where you DON’T SEE ASIANS EAT!  And this time I am following through.

Tried the Szechuan Tofu.  I was looking forward to it but ended up disappointed.  I loved the amount and variety of veggies.  Celery, Broccoli, Bell Peppers and more.  It was just too greasy.  They made it fast which was cool but goodness gracious too much oil.

TLDR: seems like standard Chinese takeout, but most things seem to be below average. Saw some mixed reviews here, but it's really close to me and sometimes you just really want late night Chinese take out, you know? I've ordered from here twice and was quite satisfied the first time with the veggie fried rice. Even without meat it had good flavor and so I was hopeful about their other dishes. The dough on the steamed dumplings was pretty chewy, but didn't have high hopes for them since they're probably made mostly to be fried. Was quite disappointed with my second order of szechuan tofu and fried cheese wontons. The tofu dish was straight up bland and the wontons were underfilled, crunchy on the edges, and tough in the center. If I ever go back, I'll stick to the fried rice and nothing else.
